event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in only a 7.35% probability of a 50+ basis point cut in October. While the Fed has signaled two more cuts by year-end (totaling 50 basis points), it's unlikely they would do a 50+ basis point cut in a single meeting. The Fed just cut rates by 25 basis points in September and signaled a gradual approach. A 50+ bps cut would be aggressive and not in line with their recent messaging about a measured approach. The probability of this outcome is likely lower than 7.35%, making it overpriced.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in a 78.5% probability of a 25 basis point cut in October. This aligns with the Fed's recent signals that they expect to make two more cuts by year-end, with one likely in October. The Fed just cut rates by 25 basis points in September and indicated a gradual approach to further easing. This market appears to be fairly priced based on current signals, but there's still some value in taking a small position in line with the Fed's guidance.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in a 14.5% probability of no change in Fed interest rates in October. Given that the Fed just signaled two more cuts by year-end and has already cut rates in September, the probability of no change seems low. The Fed has clearly indicated they see a need for further easing. This market appears to be underpriced, making it attractive to bet against (bet on 'No').

market_investment_decisions.market_question: No change in Fed interest rates after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is pricing in only a 0.75% probability of a rate increase in October. Given the current economic conditions with the Fed already cutting rates and signaling more cuts, a rate increase seems extremely unlikely. The Fed has shifted to an easing cycle. This market is essentially a near-zero probability event, making it overpriced even at 0.75%. However, given the small allocation, we'll avoid taking a position here.
